Analyze the following PlantUML use case model and detect if it contains any antipatterns.
Base your analysis solely on the model provided. Do not use any outside knowledge.


PlantUML Model:
@startuml
' Version 1 – contains Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

actor "User" as A1
actor "Administrator" as A2

rectangle "Cloud Storage Service" {
  usecase "Browse Files" as UC1
  usecase "Upload File" as UC2
  usecase "Download File" as UC3
  usecase "Manage User Accounts" as UC4
  usecase "Validate File Size" as UC5
}

A1 --> UC1
A1 --> UC2
A1 --> UC3
A2 --> UC4

UC2 ..> UC5 : <<include>>

@enduml


Answer:
Antipattern Detected: Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

   Constructs Involved: Upload File (UC2), Validate File Size (UC5), include relationship from UC2 to UC5
   Explanation: "Validate File Size" (UC5) is an inclusion use case that is included by only one use case ("Upload File" / UC2). It is not associated with any actor directly. It does not include or extend any other use case, is not extended by any use case, and has no generalization relationships. "Validate File Size" represents a sub-step of the upload process rather than a complete, independently valuable service observable to a user. This is a textbook instance of Functional Decomposition via the include relationship — the developer has decomposed the internal mechanics of uploading a file into a separate inclusion use case that provides no standalone value.
